    {/* ============ Thesis ============ */}
    <section class="thesis wrap tight reveal" data-section="thesis">
      <div class="chapter"><span class="no">01</span><span class="lbl">Why this yatra · why now</span><span class="rule"></span></div>
      <p class="quote">A Series C buys reach. The risk is spending it on more features for the metro flyer Scapia already won. <span class="lime">The growth is somewhere else: the next ten million, who travel for faith first and fly for the first time.</span></p>
      <p class="tail">Two traps follow a raise built on "more offerings": <strong>feature sprawl</strong> and rising <strong>acquisition cost</strong> as the easy metro base runs dry. Anil Goteti framed the goal as "products that help our users travel and lead richer lives." The three waypoints below sequence exactly that, for the customer the funding is actually chasing.</p>
    </section>

    {/* ============ Route ============ */}
    <section class="route wrap reveal" data-section="route">
      <div class="chapter"><span class="no">02</span><span class="lbl">The route · three waypoints</span><span class="rule"></span></div>

      <div class="ways">

        {/* Waypoint 01 */}
        <article class="way" data-section="stop_pilgrimage">
          <span class="node" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="connector" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <div class="loc">
            <span class="ghost" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
            <div class="coord">Waypoint 01 · 13.63°N 79.42°E · Tirupati</div>
            <h3>Start where India already travels</h3>
            <div class="one">The biggest first journey is not a holiday. It is a pilgrimage.</div>
            <p class="gap">Zero forex and international lounges speak to the <em>metro outbound flyer</em>. But the 7x growth and the next ten million sit in Tier 2 and Tier 3, where the highest-intent, group-sized, repeat travel is faith: <strong>Tirupati, Vaishno Devi, the Char Dham, Shirdi, the Kumbh</strong>. No premium travel-fintech is built for it.</p>
            <div class="build">
              <div class="bl">What I would build</div>
              <p>A purpose-built pilgrimage product: <strong>darshan and queue bookings</strong>, verified stays near the temple, group coordination for families, and Coins that mean something on a route people take every single year.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="win"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="23 6 13.5 15.5 8.5 10.5 1 18"/><polyline points="17 6 23 6 23 12"/></svg><span><strong>Why it wins:</strong> pilgrimage is repeat, seasonal, and word-of-mouth. One trusted family brings the next ten. The lowest-cost door into the exact customer the Series C is chasing.</span></div>
          </div>
        </article>

        {/* Waypoint 02 */}
        <article class="way" data-section="stop_firsttimer">
          <span class="node" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="connector" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <div class="loc">
            <span class="ghost" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
            <div class="coord">Waypoint 02 · 25.45°N 82.86°E · Varanasi</div>
            <h3>Build for the first journey, not the hundredth</h3>
            <div class="one">The seasoned flyer is not the next customer. The first-timer is.</div>
            <p class="gap">The app assumes travel fluency. It expects you to know what a lounge is, how forex works, how to read a boarding pass. The next ten million are often taking a <strong>first flight</strong>. The barrier is not reward value. It is <em>confidence and anxiety</em>.</p>
            <div class="build">
              <div class="bl">What I would build</div>
              <p>Re-centre on the first-timer: <strong>vernacular, plain-language onboarding</strong>, a guided "your first flight" walkthrough from booking to boarding, domestic value front and centre, and a lounge made to feel welcoming rather than intimidating.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="win"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="23 6 13.5 15.5 8.5 10.5 1 18"/><polyline points="17 6 23 6 23 12"/></svg><span><strong>Why it wins:</strong> win someone's first journey and you own every journey after it. The cheapest, stickiest loyalty there is, and invisible to competitors fighting over frequent flyers.</span></div>
          </div>
        </article>

        {/* Waypoint 03 */}
        <article class="way" data-section="stop_saathi">
          <span class="node" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="connector" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <div class="loc">
            <span class="ghost" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
            <div class="coord">Waypoint 03 · reach · 22 languages</div>
            <h3>A companion who speaks your language</h3>
            <div class="one">You met her at the top of this map. This is why she matters.</div>
            <p class="gap">AI-first cannot only mean a smarter backend. For a first-time pilgrim in their own language, the unlock is a companion that <strong>holds their hand across the whole journey</strong>: by voice, on WhatsApp, with no new app to learn.</p>
            <div class="build">
              <div class="bl">What I would build</div>
              <p><strong>Yatra Saathi.</strong> A vernacular, voice-first AI travel companion. She books, reminds, guides through the airport, handles delays, and answers in the traveller's own language. She is how Waypoints 01 and 02 scale to millions without a call centre.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="win"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="23 6 13.5 15.5 8.5 10.5 1 18"/><polyline points="17 6 23 6 23 12"/></svg><span><strong>Why it wins:</strong> the truest expression of the AI-native bet the Series C is funding, pointed at the customer who needs it most. The one feature a metro-built competitor will not think to build.</span></div>
          </div>
        </article>

        {/* Destination */}
        <div class="dest reveal">
          <span class="flag" aria-hidden="true"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 22V4M5 4h13l-2.5 4L18 12H5"/></svg></span>
          <div class="dl">Destination reached</div>
          <p>The default travel-money companion for the next India. Pilgrimage opens the door, the first-timer experience earns the trust, and <span class="lime">Yatra Saathi carries it to millions.</span></p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ============ Cartographer ============ */}
    <section class="carto wrap tight reveal" data-section="cartographer">
      <div class="chapter"><span class="no">03</span><span class="lbl">The cartographer</span><span class="rule"></span></div>
      <div class="carto-panel">
        <div class="carto-top">
          <img class="portrait" src="/firstclub/sagar-4.jpg" alt="Sagar Ahuja" loading="lazy" />
          <div>
            <h2>Why trust this map <span class="lime">to me.</span></h2>
            <div class="role">Senior Product Leader · 11 yrs · available now</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="carto-body">I have spent my career building consumer products at scale for exactly this user: <strong>mass-market India, often first-time, often not in English</strong>. That is the same person Scapia's next ten million will be. And Yatra Saathi above is not a slide about AI. It is a <em>working voice product I built for this page</em>, which is how I work.</p>
